<subSubSection id="C32E657EC6334339FF03FF32FD6C6CF6" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B8B36F5C6334339FF03FF32FE336FCC" blockId="1.[151,1192,153,251]" box="[151,392,225,251]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">
(
<figureCitation id="130F2A70C6334339FF0BFF32FEAE6FCC" box="[159,277,225,251]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 1–4" captionStart-1="FIGURES 5–10" captionStart-2="FIGURES 11–12" captionStartId-0="2.[151,264,1920,1945]" captionStartId-1="3.[151,264,1775,1800]" captionStartId-2="4.[151,264,1180,1205]" captionTargetBox-0="[378,1254,247,1784]" captionTargetBox-1="[160,1427,218,1714]" captionTargetBox-2="[162,1432,459,1147]" captionTargetId-0="figure@2.[149,1438,178,1897]" captionTargetId-1="figure@3.[151,1436,209,1721]" captionTargetId-2="figure@4.[151,1436,454,1149]" captionTargetPageId-0="2" captionTargetPageId-1="3" captionTargetPageId-2="4" captionText-0="FIGURES 1–4. Habitus photos of Amystax urara sp. nov. 1. male (Holotype), 2. female (paratype), 3. male (paratype), 4. female (paratype)." captionText-1="FIGURES 5–10. Habitat, habitus and adult host plants of Amystax urara sp. nov. 5. Habitat in Nageishidaira (ca. 1,700 m a.s.l.), 6. adult, female, 7. ditto, male, 8. ditto, female, 9. Pieris, 10. Buxus microphylla var. japonica." captionText-2="FIGURES 11–12. Pronotum and elytral base of Amystax spp. 11. A. urara sp. nov., 12. A. yakushimanus Nakamura et Morimoto (the arrows a and b indicate a costa along basal margin of elytra and a scale of strial puncture, respectively)." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3667189" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3667191" figureDoi-2="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3667193" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/3667189/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/3667191/files/figure.png" httpUri-2="https://zenodo.org/record/3667193/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Figs. 1–11</figureCitation>
&amp; 
<figureCitation id="130F2A70C6334339FEADFF32FE3A6FCC" box="[313,385,225,251]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–17" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1947,1972]" captionTargetBox="[166,1415,186,1905]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,174,1927]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 13–17. Aedeagus and spermatheca of Amystax urara sp. nov. 13. Aedeagus, dorsal, 14. ditto, lateral with tegmen. 15. terminal part of flagellum, lateral and enlarged, 16. 9thsternite and spiculum gastrale, 17. spermatheca." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3667195" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3667195/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">13–17</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8B36F5C6334339FF03FEF0FB926E08" blockId="1.[151,1437,291,1534]" box="[151,1065,291,319]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">
<emphasis id="B940EAE7C6334339FF03FEF0FE926E09" bold="true" box="[151,297,291,318]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Description.</emphasis>
Male. Length: 5.8–7.0 mm (including rostrum); width: 2.0– 
<quantity id="4CCC9B10C6334339FC58FEF7FB9E6E08" box="[972,1061,292,319]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" unit="mm" value="2.4">2.4 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8B36F5C6334339FF53FE9BFEFC6EFA" blockId="1.[151,1437,291,1534]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">
Brownish to blackish brown; antennae and legs reddish to brownish black; scaling variable (
<figureCitation id="130F2A70C6334339FB40FE9BFA856E55" box="[1236,1342,328,354]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1920,1945]" captionTargetBox="[378,1254,247,1784]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[149,1438,178,1897]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Habitus photos of Amystax urara sp. nov. 1. male (Holotype), 2. female (paratype), 3. male (paratype), 4. female (paratype)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3667189" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3667189/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Figs. 1–4</figureCitation>
&amp; 
<figureCitation id="130F2A70C6334339FAF6FE9BFA346E54" box="[1378,1423,328,355]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1775,1800]" captionTargetBox="[160,1427,218,1714]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,209,1721]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–10. Habitat, habitus and adult host plants of Amystax urara sp. nov. 5. Habitat in Nageishidaira (ca. 1,700 m a.s.l.), 6. adult, female, 7. ditto, male, 8. ditto, female, 9. Pieris, 10. Buxus microphylla var. japonica." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3667191" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3667191/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">6–8</figureCitation>
), dense, scales ovate to circular, grayish brown to ash green with metallic shimmer (or luster); pronotum with stripes; elytra with transverse band behind middle between third intervals, sometimes band indefinite; underside with only hair-like scales.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8B36F5C6334339FF53FE04FC896DDC" blockId="1.[151,1437,291,1534]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Head 1.4 times as wide as rostrum; rostrum 1.2 times as long as wide, widest and weakly depressed at base, with faint marginal carina at epistome; postmentum with pair of long setae at middle; eyes moderately convex, exterior contour in dorsal aspect angled about 45º at junction to basal side of rostrum. Pronotum 1.3–1.4 times as wide as head, nearly as wide as long, widest slightly before middle, weakly arcuate at sides; disc wrinkled, without granules or median furrow. Scutellum triangular, bare. Elytra 1.6–1.7 times as long as wide, widest at basal fifth, neither costate across basal margin nor sinuate at side margin; intervals flat, with row of subrecumbent decurved scale-like setae, each slightly longer than one scale on dorsum and becoming longer, inclined on declivity; striae weakly punctate, each puncture filled with lanceolate scale.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8B36F5C6334339FF53FD26FC556C05" blockId="1.[151,1437,291,1534]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">
Terminalia as illustrated (
<figureCitation id="130F2A70C6334339FE72FD26FDD46C27" box="[486,623,757,784]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–17" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1947,1972]" captionTargetBox="[166,1415,186,1905]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,174,1927]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 13–17. Aedeagus and spermatheca of Amystax urara sp. nov. 13. Aedeagus, dorsal, 14. ditto, lateral with tegmen. 15. terminal part of flagellum, lateral and enlarged, 16. 9thsternite and spiculum gastrale, 17. spermatheca." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3667195" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3667195/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Figs. 13–16</figureCitation>
); aedeagal body nearly as long as apodeme, with apical part tapered and attenuate apically; flagellum very long, longer than total length of aedeagus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8B36F5C6334339FF53FCEFFC626C60" blockId="1.[151,1437,291,1534]" box="[199,985,827,855]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">
Female. Length: 
<quantity id="4CCC9B10C6334339FE12FCE8FDB66C60" box="[390,525,827,855]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.1" metricValueMax="6.5" metricValueMin="5.7" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" unit="mm" value="6.1" valueMax="6.5" valueMin="5.7">5.7–6.5 mm</quantity>
(including rostrum); width: 
<quantity id="4CCC9B10C6334339FCDFFCEFFC6E6C60" box="[843,981,828,855]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.25" metricValueMax="2.3" metricValueMin="2.2" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" unit="mm" value="2.25" valueMax="2.3" valueMin="2.2">2.2–2.3 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8B36F5C6334339FF53FCB3FD6C6CF6" blockId="1.[151,1437,291,1534]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">
Differs from the male by the following points: scaling denser, stripes of pronotum and band of elytra often indefinite; and elytra 1.5–1.6 times as long as wide. Spermatheca (
<figureCitation id="130F2A70C6334339FC13FC57FC626CA9" box="[903,985,900,926]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–17" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1947,1972]" captionTargetBox="[166,1415,186,1905]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,174,1927]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 13–17. Aedeagus and spermatheca of Amystax urara sp. nov. 13. Aedeagus, dorsal, 14. ditto, lateral with tegmen. 15. terminal part of flagellum, lateral and enlarged, 16. 9thsternite and spiculum gastrale, 17. spermatheca." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3667195" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3667195/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
) rather large, about 
<quantity id="4CCC9B10C6334339FB2AFC50FAAF6CA9" box="[1214,1300,899,926]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" unit="mm" value="0.5">0.5 mm</quantity>
in length α, ramus and collum not differentiated and very short.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
