<subSubSection id="C32E657EC6334339FF53FBE4FCEC6BAF" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8B8B36F5C6334339FF53FBE4FCEC6BAF" blockId="1.[151,1437,291,1534]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">
<emphasis id="B940EAE7C6334339FF53FBE4FEF56B66" bold="true" box="[199,334,1079,1105]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Etymology.</emphasis>
“Urara” means beautiful things in Japanese, and is also the name of our close associate on Yakushima Island, Mrs. Urara Ogata of the Riverside Café Bar, St. Pote. The brownish gray to ash green lustrous scales of this species make it the brightest species in the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C344D76C6334339FD65FBADFCEB6BAF" authorityName="Roelofs" authorityYear="1873" box="[753,848,1150,1176]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Amystax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B940EAE7C6334339FD65FBADFCEB6BAF" box="[753,848,1150,1176]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Amystax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32E657EC6334339FF53FB72FAE96A81" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8B8B36F5C6334339FF53FB72FBC66A7D" blockId="1.[151,1437,291,1534]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">
<emphasis id="B940EAE7C6334339FF53FB72FE9C6B8B" bold="true" box="[199,295,1185,1212]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Biology.</emphasis>
Adults were found on the leaves of 
<taxonomicName id="4C344D76C6334339FD24FB71FB1E6B8B" authority="T. Yamaz." authorityName="T. Yamaz." box="[688,1189,1186,1212]" class="Insecta" family="Pieridae" genus="Pieris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="japonica" variety="yakushimensis">
<emphasis id="B940EAE7C6334339FD24FB71FCE06B8C" box="[688,859,1186,1211]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Pieris japonica</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis id="B940EAE7C6334339FC04FB71FB896B8B" box="[912,1074,1186,1212]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">yakushimensis</emphasis>
T. Yamaz.
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C344D76C6334339FB4CFB71FC936BE8" authority="(Mull. Arg. ex Miq.) Rehder et E. H. Wilson" authorityName="Rehder et E. H. Wilson" baseAuthorityName="Miq." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Buxaceae" genus="Buxus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Buxales" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="microphylla" variety="japonica">
<emphasis id="B940EAE7C6334339FB4CFB71FF166BE8" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Buxus microphylla</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis id="B940EAE7C6334339FF76FB15FEFF6BE8" box="[226,324,1222,1247]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">japonica</emphasis>
(Müll. Arg. ex Miq.) Rehder et E.H.Wilson
</taxonomicName>
from June to the middle of August. They were not found in October at the 
<typeStatus id="548F8857C6334339FECDFB39FE326A33" box="[345,393,1258,1284]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">type</typeStatus>
locality. Adults are common in July and their feeding scars were observed on leaf margins of the aforementioned shrubs (
<figureCitation id="130F2A70C6334339FE5AFADEFDE76A10" box="[462,604,1293,1319]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1775,1800]" captionTargetBox="[160,1427,218,1714]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,209,1721]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–10. Habitat, habitus and adult host plants of Amystax urara sp. nov. 5. Habitat in Nageishidaira (ca. 1,700 m a.s.l.), 6. adult, female, 7. ditto, male, 8. ditto, female, 9. Pieris, 10. Buxus microphylla var. japonica." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3667191" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3667191/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Figs. 9 &amp; 10</figureCitation>
). The microhabitat of this weevil seems to be restricted to shrubs on nearly flat or gently sloping areas at the 
<typeStatus id="548F8857C6334339FD99FAE2FD866A7C" box="[525,573,1329,1355]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">type</typeStatus>
locality; no adults were found on shrubs on slopes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8B36F5C6334339FF53FA87FAE96A81" blockId="1.[151,1437,291,1534]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">
The 
<typeStatus id="548F8857C6334339FF6DFA86FE926A58" box="[249,297,1365,1391]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">type</typeStatus>
locality, Nageishidaira, is a relatively flat, rocky site, ca. 
<quantity id="4CCC9B10C6334339FC38FA87FBB36A58" box="[940,1032,1364,1391]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" unit="m" value="1700.0">1,700 m</quantity>
a.l.s, with low-growing shrubs such as 
<taxonomicName id="4C344D76C6334339FF23FAAAFEC46AA5" authorityName="Nakai" authorityYear="1921" box="[183,383,1400,1427]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Rhododendron" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="yakushimanum">
<emphasis id="B940EAE7C6334339FF23FAAAFF736AA5" box="[183,200,1401,1426]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">R</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B940EAE7C6334339FF43FAABFEC46AA5" box="[215,383,1400,1426]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">yakushimanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C344D76C6334339FE1AFAAAFD576AA5" box="[398,748,1400,1427]" class="Insecta" family="Pieridae" genus="Pieris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="japonica" variety="yakushimensis">
<emphasis id="B940EAE7C6334339FE1AFAAAFE246AA5" box="[398,415,1401,1426]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B940EAE7C6334339FE3BFAAAFDAA6AA5" box="[431,529,1401,1426]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">japonica</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis id="B940EAE7C6334339FDDEFAABFD576AA5" box="[586,748,1400,1426]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">yakushimensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C344D76C6334339FD6FFAAAFBD16AA5" box="[763,1130,1400,1427]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Buxaceae" genus="Buxus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Buxales" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="microphylla" variety="japonica">
<emphasis id="B940EAE7C6334339FD6FFAAAFC756AA5" box="[763,974,1400,1426]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Buxus microphylla</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis id="B940EAE7C6334339FB9CFAAAFBD16AA5" box="[1032,1130,1401,1426]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">japonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Tsuge in Japanese; 
<taxonomicName id="4C344D76C6334339FACCFAAAFF766A81" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Buxaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Buxales" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Buxaceae</taxonomicName>
), etc. Weevils appeared to associate with, not only 
<taxonomicName id="4C344D76C6334339FC93FA4EFBB06A81" box="[775,1035,1436,1462]" class="Insecta" family="Pieridae" genus="Pieris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="japonica" variety="yakushimensis">
<emphasis id="B940EAE7C6334339FC93FA4EFC896A81" box="[775,818,1437,1462]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">P. j.</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis id="B940EAE7C6334339FCFDFA4FFBB06A81" box="[873,1035,1436,1462]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">yakushimensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but also 
<taxonomicName id="4C344D76C6334339FBE3FA4EFAF06A81" box="[1143,1355,1436,1462]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Buxaceae" genus="Buxus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Buxales" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="microphylla" variety="japonica">
<emphasis id="B940EAE7C6334339FBE3FA4EFB096A81" box="[1143,1202,1437,1462]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">B. m.</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis id="B940EAE7C6334339FB7DFA4EFAF06A81" box="[1257,1355,1437,1462]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">japonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32E657EC6334339FF53FA13FA2769DF" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B8B36F5C6334339FF53FA13FBB96ACA" blockId="1.[151,1437,291,1534]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">
<emphasis id="B940EAE7C6334339FF53FA13FE806AED" bold="true" box="[199,315,1472,1498]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Remarks.</emphasis>
The new species can easily be separated from other congeners, including the recently described 
<taxonomicName id="4C344D76C6334339FF03FA37FCB36AC9" authority="Nakamura and Morimoto, 2015" authorityName="Nakamura and Morimoto" authorityYear="2015" box="[151,776,1507,1534]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Amystax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="yakushimanus">
<emphasis id="B940EAE7C6334339FF03FA37FE276ACA" box="[151,412,1507,1534]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Amystax yakushimanus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFA54B04C6334339FE37FA30FCB36AC9" author="Nakamura, T. &amp; Morimoto, K." box="[419,776,1507,1534]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" pagination="510 - 556" refId="ref2211" refString="Nakamura, T. &amp; Morimoto, K. (2015) Tribe Tanymecini. In: Morimoto, K., Nakamura, T. &amp; Kanno, K. (Eds.), The Insects of Japan. 4. Curculionoidea: Entiminae. Part 2. Coleoptera. Touka Shobo, Fukuoka, pp. 510 - 556 + 699 - 712. [in English &amp; Japanese]" type="book chapter" year="2015">Nakamura and Morimoto, 2015</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, by the following key.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8B36F5C6334339FF03F9F0FA276944" blockId="1.[151,1436,1571,1769]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">
1(2) Scales grayish brown to ash green with metallic shimmer. Rostrum with rather shallow transverse depression at base. Pronotum reticulate and without granules on disc. Elytra neither costate nor depressed along basal margin; striae weakly punctate, each puncture with lanceolate scale (
<figureCitation id="130F2A70C6334339FD85F98EFDEC6943" box="[529,599,1629,1652]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–12" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1180,1205]" captionTargetBox="[162,1432,459,1147]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,454,1149]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 11–12. Pronotum and elytral base of Amystax spp. 11. A. urara sp. nov., 12. A. yakushimanus Nakamura et Morimoto (the arrows a and b indicate a costa along basal margin of elytra and a scale of strial puncture, respectively)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3667193" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3667193/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
). Underside clothed with only hair-like scales.................. 
<taxonomicName id="4C344D76C6334339FB6CF98DFAF16944" authority="Kojima &amp; Yôro, 2020" authorityName="Kojima &amp; Yôro" authorityYear="2020" box="[1272,1354,1630,1651]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Amystax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="urara" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B940EAE7C6334339FB6CF98DFAF16944" box="[1272,1354,1630,1651]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">A. urara</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B940EAE7C6334339FAC4F98DFA276944" bold="true" box="[1360,1436,1630,1651]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A273579CC6334339FAC4F98DFA276944" box="[1360,1436,1630,1651]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8B36F5C6334339FF03F9A8FA2769DF" blockId="1.[151,1436,1571,1769]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">
2(1) Scales grayish, pale ochraceous or brownish, usually without metallic shimmer. Rostrum with more or less distinct transverse depression at base. Pronotum granulate on disc. Elytra costate along basal margin and shallowly depressed along hind margin of costa; striae coarsely punctate, each puncture with broad ovate scale (
<figureCitation id="130F2A70C6334339FCE9F966FC7E69FB" box="[893,965,1717,1740]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–12" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1180,1205]" captionTargetBox="[162,1432,459,1147]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,454,1149]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 11–12. Pronotum and elytral base of Amystax spp. 11. A. urara sp. nov., 12. A. yakushimanus Nakamura et Morimoto (the arrows a and b indicate a costa along basal margin of elytra and a scale of strial puncture, respectively)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3667193" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3667193/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
). Underside densely clothed with ovate scales........................................................................ 
<taxonomicName id="4C344D76C6334339FBA6F900FB6E69DF" authorityName="Nakamura and Morimoto" authorityYear="2015" box="[1074,1237,1747,1768]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Amystax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="yakushimanus">
<emphasis id="B940EAE7C6334339FBA6F900FB6E69DF" box="[1074,1237,1747,1768]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">A. yakushimanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and other congeners
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
